  1. (5pts) First, let us find the most frequent directors which appear in this dataset. Code is provided below.
mateys_movies %>% group_by(Directors) %>% summarize(count = n()) %>% 
  filter(count == max(count))
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##   Directors         count
##   <chr>             <int>
## 1 Christopher Nolan     9
## 2 David Fincher         9
## 3 Martin Scorsese       9

In the above code, %>% is called the pipe operator. x %>% f(y) means the same thing as f(x, y). The pipe operator is useful in making code easily readable and understandable. Note that you need to load the tidyverse library before you can use the pipe operator.

Given this, what is the above code doing, and in particular what is the purpose of the filter(count == max(count))?

group_by(Directors) creates groups of films with the same director. summarize(count = n()) counts the number of films for each director. filter(count == max(count)) only displays the counts of films from directors with the maximum number of rated films. Since Matey has rated at most 9 films from the same director, this code displays the directors and number of film ratings (9) for directors for whom Matey has rated 9 films.

In class we discussed marginal distributions for categorical variables; here well examine the marginal distributions of the movie_period and duration variables. Do this by calculating the counts, proportions, and percentages of each variable. (Code is provided for duration; write the same code for movie_period.) Report your general observations in one sentence for each variable.

#  Get counts, proportions, and percentages for duration
duration_marginal <- mateys_movies %>%
  group_by(duration) %>%
  summarize(count = n(), 
            total = nrow(mateys_movies),
            proportion = round(count / total, 4),
            percentage = proportion * 100)
duration_marginal
## # A tibble: 3 x 5
##   duration count total proportion percentage
##   <fct>    <int> <int>      <dbl>      <dbl>
## 1 Short       53   737     0.0719       7.19
## 2 Medium     395   737     0.536       53.6 
## 3 Long       289   737     0.392       39.2
movie_period_marginal <- mateys_movies %>%
  group_by(movie_period) %>%
  summarize(count = n(),
            total = nrow(mateys_movies),
            proportion = round(count / total, 4),
            percentage = proportion * 100)
movie_period_marginal
## # A tibble: 3 x 5
##   movie_period count total proportion percentage
##   <fct>        <int> <int>      <dbl>      <dbl>
## 1 Old             26   737     0.0353       3.53
## 2 Recent         141   737     0.191       19.1 
## 3 New            570   737     0.773       77.3

Out of Mateys rated movies, 7.19% of movies are short, 53.6% of movies are medium length, and 39.2% of movies are long. In terms of movie period, 3.53% of movies are old, 19.1% of movies are recent, and 77.3% of movies are new.

Notice how, within the summarize() function, we can sequentially define a new variable and then refer to that new variable later on. For example, within summarize(), we first define a variable total, and then we refer to total when defining proportion.

  1. (10pts) Lets test this statistically. Run a chi-square test to check your friends assertion: chisq.test(duration_marginal$count) will check to see if the proportions in each category are the same. After you run the test, answer the following questions:
chisq.test(duration_marginal$count)
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  duration_marginal$count
## X-squared = 249.52, df = 2, p-value < 2.2e-16
  • What is the p-value for this test?

We see that the p-value is quite small; less than \(2.2 \cdot 10^{-16}\).

  • What is your formal conclusion from this test?

The null hypothesis is that the proportions of films in all categories are the same. We clearly reject the null hypothesis at \(\alpha = 0.05\) (or any other reasonable significance level). This is strong evidence that the proportions of films in all categories are not the same.

  1. (10pts) In the previous part you used the chi-squared test to assess if there is a significantly different number of movies in each duration category. We can also use confidence intervals to assess statistical significance.

Notice that the data frame duration_marginal already has the proportions in each duration category and the total number of movies, which is exactly what you need to compute the confidence intervals for each proportion. Fill in the code below to display the lower and upper bounds for the 95% confidence intervals for the proportions.

#write code here for the CI lower bound
#change 0 to something else
duration_marginal$proportion - qnorm(0.975)*sqrt((1-duration_marginal$proportion)*duration_marginal$proportion/duration_marginal$total)
## [1] 0.05325011 0.49999559 0.35685246
#write code here for the CI upper bound
#change 0 to something else
duration_marginal$proportion + qnorm(0.975)*sqrt((1-duration_marginal$proportion)*duration_marginal$proportion/duration_marginal$total)
## [1] 0.09054989 0.57200441 0.42734754

Hint: We talked about how to compute the confidence interval for a proportion in class, so it may be helpful to revisit your lecture notes. Remember that the confidence interval involves the alpha/2 quantile from a standard Normal distribution. In this case, alpha = 0.05. The quantile can be computed as:

qnorm(0.975)
## [1] 1.959964

This is the classic 1.96 (sometimes rounded to 2).

After youve successfully displayed your confidence intervals: Which confidence intervals dont overlap? What does this suggest, and how does this differ from the conclusion we could make from the chi-squared test?

None of the confidence intervals overlap - this suggests that there is a significant difference in proportions among all three categories (i.e., none of them are equal). From the chi-squared test, we could only conclude that not all of the proportions were equal; here we are able to conclude that indeed none of them are equal to each other.

Problem 2: 2D Bar Charts and Identifying Marginal Distributions (25 points)

Although were focusing on 1D categorical data this week, in this problem well start to look at 2D categorical data, which well discuss in depth next week. In particular, well explore how we can build upon bar charts to make multivariate graphics.

  1. (10pts) Here well walk through how to make a stacked bar plot, which I mentioned in class last week and well discuss in depth next week. In short, a stacked bar plot is simply a bar plot, where each bar is in turn a spine chart; as a result, it visualizes two categorical variables. Well again use the mateys_movies dataset from Problem 1. Follow these steps:
  • First, make a bar graph of weekend. Make the color of the bars something other than gray by specifying the fill variable.
  • Now we want to color the bars by the ratings variable; in other words, we want to fill the bars according to the ratings variable. So, set fill = ratings in your code.
  • At this point, you probably get an error if you run your code. Notice that you probably have fill = ratings within geom_bar() (which is fine!) However, ggplot requires all variable names to be within the aes() function; the reason is that aes() describe how variables in the data are mapped to visual properties (to quote the help documentation for that function). So, if you have fill = ratings outside of aes(), ggplot is saying, What is ratings? It must not be a variable in the mateys_movies dataset, because ratings isnt inside aes()so Im confused. To fix this issue, either (1) write aes(fill = ratings) within geom_bar(), or (2) put fill = ratings within the aes() already inside ggplot(). Either should work fine!

The goal of this problem is to make a stacked bar plot, with bars for weekend and different colors for ratings. If you get stuck here, please ask your peers and/or TAs for help.

ggplot(mateys_movies, aes(x = weekend)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = ratings))

  1. (5pts) Use your graph from Part A to discuss the marginal distribution of weekend and the marginal distribution for ratings.

By looking at the height of the bars, we can assess the marginal distribution of weekend - in particular, we can see that Matey rated more films on weekdays than on weekends. Meanwhile, by looking at the total area of each color, we can assess the marginal distribution of ratings - we see that the most common rating was medium (because there is more green area than the other colors), followed by a high rating, and finally a low rating.

  1. (10pts) Now make a stacked bar chart that involves movie_period and day_of_week such that you think its easiest to describe the marginal distribution of movie_period. After youve made your graph, explain in 1-2 sentences why you made the choices you made - i.e., how the choices you made allow you to most easily describe the marginal distribution of movie_period. (For this part, theres no need to actually describe the marginal distribution.)
ggplot(mateys_movies, aes(x = movie_period)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = day_of_week))

From the previous exercise, we found that it was easier to assess the height of bars than the area of colors. Thus, we made the height of bars in this graph correspond to movie_period, such that it is easy to assess the marginal distribution of this variable. Note that it is actually quite difficult to assess the marginal distribution of day_of_week with this plot (because there are so many colors within each bar), but that is a sacrifice we are willing to make if our main priority is displaying the marginal distribution of movie_period.

Problem 3: Adding More Categories with Facetting (30 points)

In addition to visualizing a single categorical variable, we can also create the same visualization for different categories, thereby allowing for flexible multivariate graphics. This is known as facetting, where the data is grouped according to some categorical variable, and then we create the same graphic for each group. The resulting graphs are typically displayed in a grid, where each graph is a single facet of the full graphic.

This is a popular way to show how the features of the variable(s) being displayed in a particular graphic can change depending on some other variable (usually a categorical variable).

In Problem 2 you made a stacked bar plot for weekend and ratings. Alternatively, you could make two different bar plots for ratings, corresponding to the two different values for weekend. Well demonstrate how to do this using facetting.

  1. (10pts) To make a bar plot of ratings facetted by weekend, follow these steps:
  • First, make a bar plot of ratings the standard way (where fill is specified as a color within geom_bar()).
  • Then, add + facet_grid(~ weekend) to your existing line of code.
ggplot(mateys_movies, aes(x = ratings)) + geom_bar(fill = "blue") + facet_grid(~ weekend)

You should see two bar plots graphed together, one for each value of weekend. After youve successfully made your plot, consider the following. When we have two categorical variables, there are four distributions we should consider: The marginal distribution of ratings, the marginal distribution of weekend, the conditional distribution of ratings given weekend, and the conditional distribution of weekend given ratings. (Were focusing on marginal distributions this week - well discuss conditional distributions next week.) Which plot makes it easier to see both marginal distributions: The facetted bar plot here, or the stacked bar plot in 2A? Explain your reasoning in 1-3 sentences.

It seems somewhat easier to see the marginal distributions in the stacked bar plot in 2A than the facetted bar plot here. For the stacked bar plot, it is quite easy to see one marginal distribution by looking at just the heights of the bars - meanwhile, we could deduce the other marginal distribution by looking at the total area of each color. Meanwhile, for the facetted bar plot, in order to figure out the marginal distribution of weekend, we have to compare the total area of the left facet to the total area of the right facet; meanwhile, to figure out the marginal distribution of ratings, we have to compare the total height of the low, medium, and high bars. Thus, in the facetted plot, we have to compare total areas for both marginal distributions, which seems more difficult than having to compare total areas for only one marginal distribution.

  1. (10pts) You can also display marginal distributions by adding margin = TRUE within facet_grid(). So, copy-and-paste your code from Part A and then add margin = TRUE within facet_grid(). Your submission should display a third bar plot, labeled as (all). This displays a marginal distribution - the marginal distribution of what?
ggplot(mateys_movies, aes(x = ratings)) + geom_bar(fill = "blue") + facet_grid(~ weekend, margin = TRUE)

This displays the marginal distribution for ratings.

  1. (5pts) We can also facet stacked bar plots, thereby allowing for even more dimensions. Recreate the graph in Problem 2C, but this time, facet on weekend (dont include margin = TRUE). For this part, all you have to do is make the desired graph. (You should end up with multiple facets of stacked bar plots, where each stacked bar plot involves movie_period and day_of_week.)

  1. (5pts) We can actually facet on multiple categorical variables at once. Recreate the graph in Problem 2C again, but this time facet by both weekend and ratings by adding facet_grid(weekend ~ ratings). We wont ask you to interpret this graph here, since there are four dimensions being plotted in this visual. The purpose of this problem is just to demonstrate that its pretty easy to make extensions to bar plots that allow for 3D and 4D graphs! (Of course, whether or not youd actually want to display all four variables in a single graph is another story - we will discuss this throughout the semester.)
ggplot(mateys_movies, aes(x = movie_period)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = day_of_week)) + facet_grid(weekend ~ ratings)
